<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">William Shakespeare</h1>
<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
<div id="contentSub"></div>

<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="hatnote">This article is about the poet and playwright. For other persons of the same name, see <a href="/wiki/William_Shakespeare_(disambiguation)" title="William Shakespeare (disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig">William Shakespeare (disambiguation)</a>. For other uses of "Shakespeare", see <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare_(disambiguation)" title="Shakespeare (disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig">Shakespeare (disambiguation)</a>.</div>

<p><b>William Shakespeare</b> (<span class="nowrap"><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ˈ</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ʃ/ 'sh' in 'shy'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ʃ</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/eɪ/ long 'a' in 'base'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">eɪ</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'k' in 'kind'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">k</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'s' in 'sigh'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">s</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'p' in 'pie'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">p</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ɪər/ 'ear' in 'beard'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ɪər</span></a></span><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span></span>;<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> 26 April 1564 (<a href="/wiki/Baptism" title="Baptism">baptised</a>)&#160;– 23 April 1616)<sup id="cite_ref-dates_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dates-2"><span>[</span>nb 1<span>]</span></a></sup> was an English <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Playwright" title="Playwright">playwright</a>, and actor, widely regarded as the greatest writer in the <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English language</a> and the world's pre-eminent dramatist.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> He is often called England's <a href="/wiki/List_of_national_poets" title="List of national poets" class="mw-redirect">national poet</a> and the "Bard of Avon".<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-national-cult_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-national-cult-5"><span>[</span>nb 2<span>]</span></a></sup> His extant works, including some <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_collaborations" title="Shakespeare's collaborations" class="mw-redirect">collaborations</a>, consist of about <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_plays" title="Shakespeare's plays">38 plays</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-exact-figures_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-exact-figures-6"><span>[</span>nb 3<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_sonnets" title="Shakespeare's sonnets">154 sonnets</a>, two long <a href="/wiki/Narrative_poem" title="Narrative poem" class="mw-redirect">narrative poems</a>, and a few other verses, of which the authorship of some is uncertain. His plays have been translated into every major <a href="/wiki/Modern_language" title="Modern language">living language</a> and are performed more often than those of any other playwright.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shakespeare was born and brought up in <a href="/wiki/Stratford-upon-Avon" title="Stratford-upon-Avon">Stratford-upon-Avon</a>. At the age of 18, he married <a href="/wiki/Anne_Hathaway_(Shakespeare%27s_wife)" title="Anne Hathaway (Shakespeare's wife)">Anne Hathaway</a>, with whom he had three children: <a href="/wiki/Susanna_Hall" title="Susanna Hall">Susanna</a>, and twins <a href="/wiki/Hamnet_Shakespeare" title="Hamnet Shakespeare">Hamnet</a> and <a href="/wiki/Judith_Quiney" title="Judith Quiney">Judith</a>. Between 1585 and 1592, he began a successful career in London as an actor, writer, and part-owner of a <a href="/wiki/Playing_company" title="Playing company">playing company</a> called the <a href="/wiki/Lord_Chamberlain%27s_Men" title="Lord Chamberlain's Men">Lord Chamberlain's Men</a>, later known as the <a href="/wiki/King%27s_Men_(playing_company)" title="King's Men (playing company)">King's Men</a>. He appears to have retired to Stratford around 1613 at age 49, where he died three years later. Few records of Shakespeare's private life survive, and there has been considerable speculation about such matters as <a href="/wiki/Portraits_of_Shakespeare" title="Portraits of Shakespeare">his physical appearance</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sexuality_of_William_Shakespeare" title="Sexuality of William Shakespeare">sexuality</a>, <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_religion" title="Shakespeare's religion">religious beliefs</a>, and whether the works attributed to him were <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare_authorship_question" title="Shakespeare authorship question">written by others</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shakespeare produced most of his known work between 1589 and 1613.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-play-dates_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-play-dates-10"><span>[</span>nb 4<span>]</span></a></sup> His early plays were mainly <a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_comedy" title="Shakespearean comedy">comedies</a> and <a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_history" title="Shakespearean history">histories</a> and these works remain regarded as some of the best work produced in these genres. He then wrote mainly <a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_tragedy" title="Shakespearean tragedy">tragedies</a> until about 1608, including <i><a href="/wiki/Hamlet" title="Hamlet">Hamlet</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Othello" title="Othello">Othello</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/King_Lear" title="King Lear">King Lear</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/Macbeth" title="Macbeth">Macbeth</a></i>, considered some of the finest works in the English language. In his last phase, he wrote tragicomedies, also known as <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_late_romances" title="Shakespeare's late romances">romances</a>, and collaborated with other playwrights.</p>
<p>Many of his plays were published in editions of varying quality and accuracy during his lifetime. In 1623, <a href="/wiki/John_Heminges" title="John Heminges">John Heminges</a> and <a href="/wiki/Henry_Condell" title="Henry Condell">Henry Condell</a>, two friends and fellow actors of Shakespeare, published the <a href="/wiki/First_Folio" title="First Folio">First Folio</a>, a collected edition of his dramatic works that included all but two of the plays now recognised as Shakespeare's. It was prefaced with a poem by <a href="/wiki/Ben_Jonson" title="Ben Jonson">Ben Jonson</a>, in which Shakespeare is hailed, presciently, as "not of an age, but for all time".<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> In the 20th and 21st century, his work has been repeatedly adopted and rediscovered by new movements in scholarship and performance. His plays remain highly popular today and are constantly studied, performed, and reinterpreted in diverse cultural and political contexts throughout the world.</p>
<p></p>

<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Life">Life</span></h2>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_life" title="Shakespeare's life">Shakespeare's life</a></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_life">Early life</span></h3>
<p>William Shakespeare was the son of <a href="/wiki/John_Shakespeare" title="John Shakespeare">John Shakespeare</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Alderman" title="Alderman">alderman</a> and a successful glover originally from <a href="/wiki/Snitterfield" title="Snitterfield">Snitterfield</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mary_Shakespeare" title="Mary Shakespeare">Mary Arden</a>, the daughter of an affluent landowning farmer.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> He was born in <a href="/wiki/Stratford-upon-Avon" title="Stratford-upon-Avon">Stratford-upon-Avon</a> and baptised there on 26 April 1564. His actual date of birth remains unknown, but is traditionally observed on 23 April, <a href="/wiki/Saint_George%27s_Day" title="Saint George's Day" class="mw-redirect">Saint George's Day</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup> This date, which can be traced back to an 18th-century scholar's mistake, has proved appealing to biographers, since Shakespeare died 23 April 1616.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> He was the third child of eight and the eldest surviving son.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Although no attendance records for the period survive, most biographers agree that Shakespeare was probably educated at the <a href="/wiki/King_Edward_VI_School_Stratford-upon-Avon" title="King Edward VI School Stratford-upon-Avon" class="mw-redirect">King's New School</a> in Stratford,<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> a free school chartered in 1553,<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> about a quarter-mile (400 m) from his home. <a href="/wiki/Grammar_school" title="Grammar school">Grammar schools</a> varied in quality during the Elizabethan era, but grammar school curricula were largely similar, the basic <a href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a> text was standardised by royal decree,<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> and the school would have provided an intensive education in grammar based upon Latin <a href="/wiki/Classics" title="Classics">classical</a> authors.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:William_Shakespeares_birthplace,_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg/220px-William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg" width="220" height="120" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg/330px-William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg/440px-William_Shakespeares_birthplace%2C_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="435" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:William_Shakespeares_birthplace,_Stratford-upon-Avon_26l2007.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
John Shakespeare's house, believed to be <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_Birthplace" title="Shakespeare's Birthplace">Shakespeare's birthplace</a>, in <a href="/wiki/Stratford-upon-Avon" title="Stratford-upon-Avon">Stratford-upon-Avon</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>At the age of 18, Shakespeare married the 26-year-old <a href="/wiki/Anne_Hathaway_(Shakespeare%27s_wife)" title="Anne Hathaway (Shakespeare's wife)">Anne Hathaway</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Consistory_court" title="Consistory court">consistory court</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Anglican_Diocese_of_Worcester" title="Anglican Diocese of Worcester">Diocese of Worcester</a> issued a marriage licence on 27 November 1582. The next day, two of Hathaway's neighbours posted bonds guaranteeing that no lawful claims impeded the marriage.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> The ceremony may have been arranged in some haste, since the Worcester <a href="/wiki/Chancellor" title="Chancellor">chancellor</a> allowed the <a href="/wiki/Banns_of_marriage" title="Banns of marriage">marriage banns</a> to be read once instead of the usual three times,<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup> and six months after the marriage Anne gave birth to a daughter, <a href="/wiki/Susanna_Hall" title="Susanna Hall">Susanna</a>, baptised 26 May 1583.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup> Twins, son <a href="/wiki/Hamnet_Shakespeare" title="Hamnet Shakespeare">Hamnet</a> and daughter <a href="/wiki/Judith_Quiney" title="Judith Quiney">Judith</a>, followed almost two years later and were baptised 2 February 1585.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup> Hamnet died of unknown causes at the age of 11 and was buried 11 August 1596.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakespeare1COA.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Shakespeare1COA.png/220px-Shakespeare1COA.png" width="220" height="274" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Shakespeare1COA.png/330px-Shakespeare1COA.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Shakespeare1COA.png/440px-Shakespeare1COA.png 2x" data-file-width="700" data-file-height="871" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakespeare1COA.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Shakespeare's coat of arms, featuring a spear as a <a href="/wiki/Canting_arms" title="Canting arms">pun</a> on the family name.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>After the birth of the twins, Shakespeare left few historical traces until he is mentioned as part of the London theatre scene in 1592. The exception is the appearance of his name in the 'complaints bill' of a law case before the Queen's Bench court at Westminster dated <a href="/wiki/Michaelmas_Term" title="Michaelmas Term" class="mw-redirect">Michaelmas Term</a> 1588 and 9 October 1589.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> Scholars refer to the years between 1585 and 1592 as Shakespeare's "lost years".<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26"><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup> Biographers attempting to account for this period have reported many <a href="//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/apocryphal" class="extiw" title="wikt:apocryphal">apocryphal</a> stories. <a href="/wiki/Nicholas_Rowe_(writer)" title="Nicholas Rowe (writer)">Nicholas Rowe</a>, Shakespeare's first biographer, recounted a Stratford legend that Shakespeare fled the town for London to escape prosecution for deer <a href="/wiki/Poaching" title="Poaching">poaching</a> in the estate of local squire <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Lucy" title="Thomas Lucy">Thomas Lucy</a>. Shakespeare is also supposed to have taken his revenge on Lucy by writing a scurrilous ballad about him.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup> Another 18th-century story has Shakespeare starting his theatrical career minding the horses of theatre patrons in London.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/John_Aubrey" title="John Aubrey">John Aubrey</a> reported that Shakespeare had been a country schoolmaster.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup> Some 20th-century scholars have suggested that Shakespeare may have been employed as a schoolmaster by Alexander Hoghton of <a href="/wiki/Lancashire" title="Lancashire">Lancashire</a>, a Catholic landowner who named a certain "William Shakeshafte" in his will.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30"><span>[</span>26<span>]</span></a></sup> Little evidence substantiates such stories other than <a href="//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/hearsay" class="extiw" title="wikt:hearsay">hearsay</a> collected after his death, and Shakeshafte was a common name in the Lancashire area.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31"><span>[</span>27<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="London_and_theatrical_career">London and theatrical career</span></h3>
<div class="quotebox" style="float: right; clear: right; margin: 0.5em 0 0.8em 1.4em; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #aaa; font-size: 88%; background-color: #F9F9F9;">
<div class="" style="position: relative; text-align: left;">
<div>
<div class="poem">
<p>"All the world's a stage,<br />
and all the men and women merely players:<br />
they have their exits and their entrances;<br />
and one man in his time plays many parts..."</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div style="text-align: left;">—<i><a href="/wiki/As_You_Like_It" title="As You Like It">As You Like It</a></i>, Act II, Scene 7, 139–42<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32"><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
<p>It is not known exactly when Shakespeare began writing, but contemporary allusions and records of performances show that several of his plays were on the London stage by 1592.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33"><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup> By then, he was sufficiently well known in London to be attacked in print by the playwright <a href="/wiki/Robert_Greene_(dramatist)" title="Robert Greene (dramatist)">Robert Greene</a> in his <i><a href="/wiki/Greene%27s_Groats-Worth_of_Wit" title="Greene's Groats-Worth of Wit">Groats-Worth of Wit</a></i>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>...there is an upstart Crow, beautified with our feathers, that with his <i>Tiger's heart wrapped in a Player's hide</i>, supposes he is as well able to bombast out a blank verse as the best of you: and being an absolute <i>Johannes factotum</i>, is in his own conceit the only Shake-scene in a country.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34"><span>[</span>30<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Scholars differ on the exact meaning of these words,<sup id="cite_ref-SG213_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SG213-35"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup> but most agree that Greene is accusing Shakespeare of reaching above his rank in trying to match university-educated writers such as <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Marlowe" title="Christopher Marlowe">Christopher Marlowe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Nashe" title="Thomas Nashe">Thomas Nashe</a> and Greene himself (the <a href="/wiki/University_Wits" title="University Wits">"university wits"</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup> The italicised phrase parodying the line "Oh, tiger's heart wrapped in a woman's hide" from Shakespeare's <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_VI,_Part_3" title="Henry VI, Part 3">Henry VI, Part 3</a></i>, along with the pun "Shake-scene", identifies Shakespeare as Greene's target. Here <i><a href="/wiki/Jack_of_all_trades,_master_of_none" title="Jack of all trades, master of none">Johannes Factotum</a></i>—"Jack of all trades"— means a second-rate tinkerer with the work of others, rather than the more common "universal genius".<sup id="cite_ref-SG213_35-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SG213-35"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Greene's attack is the earliest surviving mention of Shakespeare's career in the theatre. Biographers suggest that his career may have begun any time from the mid-1580s to just before Greene's remarks.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38"><span>[</span>34<span>]</span></a></sup> From 1594, Shakespeare's plays were performed by only the <a href="/wiki/Lord_Chamberlain%27s_Men" title="Lord Chamberlain's Men">Lord Chamberlain's Men</a>, a company owned by a group of players, including Shakespeare, that soon became the leading <a href="/wiki/Playing_company" title="Playing company">playing company</a> in London.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39"><span>[</span>35<span>]</span></a></sup> After the death of <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_I_of_England" title="Elizabeth I of England">Queen Elizabeth</a> in 1603, the company was awarded a royal patent by the new king, <a href="/wiki/James_I_of_England" title="James I of England" class="mw-redirect">James I</a>, and changed its name to the <a href="/wiki/King%27s_Men_(playing_company)" title="King's Men (playing company)">King's Men</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40"><span>[</span>36<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In 1599, a partnership of company members built their own theatre on the south bank of the <a href="/wiki/River_Thames" title="River Thames">River Thames</a>, which they called the <a href="/wiki/Globe_Theatre" title="Globe Theatre">Globe</a>. In 1608, the partnership also took over the <a href="/wiki/Blackfriars_Theatre" title="Blackfriars Theatre">Blackfriars indoor theatre</a>. Records of Shakespeare's property purchases and investments indicate that the company made him a wealthy man.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41"><span>[</span>37<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1597, he bought the second-largest house in Stratford, <a href="/wiki/New_Place" title="New Place">New Place</a>, and in 1605, he invested in a share of the parish <a href="/wiki/Tithes" title="Tithes" class="mw-redirect">tithes</a> in Stratford.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42"><span>[</span>38<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Some of Shakespeare's plays were published in <a href="/wiki/Quarto_(binding)" title="Quarto (binding)" class="mw-redirect">quarto</a> editions from 1594. By 1598, his name had become a selling point and began to appear on the <a href="/wiki/Title_page" title="Title page">title pages</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43"><span>[</span>39<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare continued to act in his own and other plays after his success as a playwright. The 1616 edition of <a href="/wiki/Ben_Jonson" title="Ben Jonson">Ben Jonson</a>'s <i>Works</i> names him on the cast lists for <i><a href="/wiki/Every_Man_in_His_Humour" title="Every Man in His Humour">Every Man in His Humour</a></i> (1598) and <i><a href="/wiki/Sejanus_His_Fall" title="Sejanus His Fall">Sejanus His Fall</a></i> (1603).<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44"><span>[</span>40<span>]</span></a></sup> The absence of his name from the 1605 cast list for Jonson's <i><a href="/wiki/Volpone" title="Volpone">Volpone</a></i> is taken by some scholars as a sign that his acting career was nearing its end.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45"><span>[</span>41<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/First_Folio" title="First Folio">First Folio</a> of 1623, however, lists Shakespeare as one of "the Principal Actors in all these Plays", some of which were first staged after <i>Volpone</i>, although we cannot know for certain which roles he played.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46"><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1610, <a href="/wiki/John_Davies_of_Hereford" title="John Davies of Hereford">John Davies of Hereford</a> wrote that "good Will" played "kingly" roles.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47"><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1709, Rowe passed down a tradition that Shakespeare played the ghost of Hamlet's father.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48"><span>[</span>44<span>]</span></a></sup> Later traditions maintain that he also played Adam in <i><a href="/wiki/As_You_Like_It" title="As You Like It">As You Like It</a></i> and the Chorus in <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_V_(play)" title="Henry V (play)">Henry V</a></i>,<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup> though scholars doubt the sources of the information.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span>[</span>46<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shakespeare divided his time between London and Stratford during his career. In 1596, the year before he bought New Place as his family home in Stratford, Shakespeare was living in the parish of St. Helen's, <a href="/wiki/Bishopsgate" title="Bishopsgate">Bishopsgate</a>, north of the River Thames.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHales1904401.E2.80.932_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHales1904401.E2.80.932-51"><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span>[</span>48<span>]</span></a></sup> He moved across the river to <a href="/wiki/Southwark" title="Southwark">Southwark</a> by 1599, the year his company constructed the Globe Theatre there.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHales1904401.E2.80.932_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHales1904401.E2.80.932-51"><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53"><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup> By 1604, he had moved north of the river again, to an area north of <a href="/wiki/St_Paul%27s_Cathedral" title="St Paul's Cathedral">St Paul's Cathedral</a> with many fine houses. There he rented rooms from a French <a href="/wiki/Huguenot" title="Huguenot">Huguenot</a> named Christopher Mountjoy, a maker of ladies' wigs and other headgear.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54"><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Later_years_and_death">Later years and death</span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Nicholas_Rowe_(writer)" title="Nicholas Rowe (writer)">Rowe</a> was the first biographer to record the tradition, repeated by <a href="/wiki/Samuel_Johnson" title="Samuel Johnson">Johnson</a>, that Shakespeare retired to Stratford 'some years before his death'.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-55"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWood1806ix.E2.80.93x.2C_lxxii_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWood1806ix.E2.80.93x.2C_lxxii-56"><span>[</span>52<span>]</span></a></sup> He was still working as an actor in London in 1608; in an answer to the sharers' petition in 1635 <a href="/wiki/Cuthbert_Burbage" title="Cuthbert Burbage">Cuthbert Burbage</a> stated that after purchasing the lease of the <a href="/wiki/Blackfriars_Theatre" title="Blackfriars Theatre">Blackfriars Theatre</a> in 1608 from <a href="/wiki/Henry_Evans_(theatre)" title="Henry Evans (theatre)">Henry Evans</a>, the King's Men 'placed men players' there, 'which were <a href="/wiki/John_Heminges" title="John Heminges">Heminges</a>, <a href="/wiki/Henry_Condell" title="Henry Condell">Condell</a>, Shakespeare, etc.'.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmith1964558_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmith1964558-57"><span>[</span>53<span>]</span></a></sup> However it is perhaps relevant that the <a href="/wiki/Bubonic_plague" title="Bubonic plague">bubonic plague</a> raged in London throughout 1609.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAckroyd2006477_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAckroyd2006477-58"><span>[</span>54<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBarroll1991179.E2.80.9382_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBarroll1991179.E2.80.9382-59"><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup> The London public playhouses were repeatedly closed during extended outbreaks of the plague (a total of over 60 months closure between May 1603 and February 1610),<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60"><span>[</span>56<span>]</span></a></sup> which meant there was often no acting work. Retirement from all work was uncommon at that time.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61"><span>[</span>57<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare continued to visit London during the years 1611–1614.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_55-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-55"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1612, he was called as a witness in <i><a href="/wiki/Bellott_v._Mountjoy" title="Bellott v. Mountjoy" class="mw-redirect">Bellott v. Mountjoy</a></i>, a court case concerning the marriage settlement of Mountjoy's daughter, Mary.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62"><span>[</span>58<span>]</span></a></sup> In March 1613 he bought a <a href="/wiki/Gatehouse" title="Gatehouse">gatehouse</a> in the former <a href="/wiki/Blackfriars,_London" title="Blackfriars, London">Blackfriars</a> priory;<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63"><span>[</span>59<span>]</span></a></sup> and from November 1614 he was in London for several weeks with his son-in-law, <a href="/wiki/John_Hall_(physician)" title="John Hall (physician)">John Hall</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64"><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup> After 1610, Shakespeare wrote fewer plays, and none are attributed to him after 1613.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65"><span>[</span>61<span>]</span></a></sup> His last three plays were collaborations, probably with <a href="/wiki/John_Fletcher_(playwright)" title="John Fletcher (playwright)">John Fletcher</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66"><span>[</span>62<span>]</span></a></sup> who succeeded him as the house playwright for the King's Men.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67"><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg/170px-ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg" width="170" height="414" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg/255px-ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg/340px-ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="537" data-file-height="1309" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:ShakespeareMonument_cropped.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_funerary_monument" title="Shakespeare's funerary monument">Shakespeare's funerary monument</a> in Stratford-upon-Avon.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Shakespeare died on 23 April 1616, at the age of 52.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68"><span>[</span>64<span>]</span></a></sup> He died within a month of signing his will, a document which he begins by describing himself as being in "perfect health". There is no extant contemporary source that explains how or why he died. After half a century had passed, <a href="/wiki/John_Ward_(vicar)" title="John Ward (vicar)">John Ward</a>, the vicar of Stratford, wrote in his notebook: "Shakespeare, Drayton and Ben Jonson had a merry meeting and, it seems, drank too hard, for Shakespeare died of a fever there contracted."<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69"><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70"><span>[</span>66<span>]</span></a></sup> This is not impossible, for Shakespeare knew Jonson and Drayton. Of the tributes that started to come from fellow authors, one refers to his relatively early death: "We wondered, Shakespeare, that thou went'st so soon/From the world's stage to the grave's tiring room."<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71"><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>He was survived by his wife and two daughters. Susanna had married a physician, John Hall, in 1607,<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72"><span>[</span>68<span>]</span></a></sup> and Judith had married <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Quiney" title="Thomas Quiney">Thomas Quiney</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Vintner" title="Vintner" class="mw-redirect">vintner</a>, two months before Shakespeare's death.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73"><span>[</span>69<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare signed his last will and testament on 25 March 1616; the following day his new son-in-law, Thomas Quiney was found guilty of fathering an illegitimate son by Margaret Wheeler, who had died during childbirth. Thomas was ordered by the church court to do public penance which would have caused much shame and embarrassment for the Shakespeare family.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74"><span>[</span>70<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In his will, Shakespeare left the bulk of his large estate to his elder daughter Susanna.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75"><span>[</span>71<span>]</span></a></sup> The terms instructed that she pass it down intact to "the first son of her body".<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span>[</span>72<span>]</span></a></sup> The Quineys had three children, all of whom died without marrying.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span>[</span>73<span>]</span></a></sup> The Halls had one child, Elizabeth, who married twice but died without children in 1670, ending Shakespeare's direct line.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78"><span>[</span>74<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare's will scarcely mentions his wife, Anne, who was probably entitled to one third of his estate automatically.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79"><span>[</span>75<span>]</span></a></sup> He did make a point, however, of leaving her "my second best bed", a bequest that has led to much speculation.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span>[</span>76<span>]</span></a></sup> Some scholars see the bequest as an insult to Anne, whereas others believe that the second-best bed would have been the matrimonial bed and therefore rich in significance.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81"><span>[</span>77<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shakespeare was buried in the <a href="/wiki/Chancel" title="Chancel">chancel</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Trinity_Church,_Stratford-upon-Avon" title="Holy Trinity Church, Stratford-upon-Avon" class="mw-redirect">Holy Trinity Church</a> two days after his death.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82"><span>[</span>78<span>]</span></a></sup> The epitaph carved into the stone slab covering his grave includes a curse against moving his bones, which was carefully avoided during restoration of the church in 2008:<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83"><span>[</span>79<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg/220px-Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg/330px-Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg/440px-Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1536" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakespeare_grave_-Stratford-upon-Avon_-3June2007.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Shakespeare's grave, sitting next to Anne Shakespeare, his wife, and to <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Nash" title="Thomas Nash">Thomas Nash</a>, the husband of his granddaughter.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="poem">
<p><i>Good frend for Iesvs sake forbeare,</i><br />
<i>To digg the dvst encloased heare.</i><br />
<i>Bleste be <a href="/wiki/File:Middle_English_the.svg" class="image" title="Middle English the.svg"><img alt="Middle English the.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Middle_English_the.svg/8px-Middle_English_the.svg.png" width="8" height="19" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Middle_English_the.svg/12px-Middle_English_the.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Middle_English_the.svg/16px-Middle_English_the.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="8" data-file-height="19" /></a> man <a href="/wiki/File:Middle_English_that.svg" class="image" title="Middle English that.svg"><img alt="Middle English that.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/9px-Middle_English_that.svg.png" width="9" height="20" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/14px-Middle_English_that.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/18px-Middle_English_that.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="9" data-file-height="20" /></a> spares thes stones,</i><br />
<i>And cvrst be he <a href="/wiki/File:Middle_English_that.svg" class="image" title="Middle English that.svg"><img alt="Middle English that.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/9px-Middle_English_that.svg.png" width="9" height="20" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/14px-Middle_English_that.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Middle_English_that.svg/18px-Middle_English_that.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="9" data-file-height="20" /></a> moves my bones.</i><sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84"><span>[</span>80<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-thorn_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-thorn-85"><span>[</span>nb 5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</div>
<p>(Modern spelling: <i>Good friend, for Jesus' sake forbear, | To dig the dust enclosed here. | Blessed be the man that spares these stones, | And cursed be he that moves my bones.</i>)</p>
<p>Sometime before 1623, a <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_funerary_monument" title="Shakespeare's funerary monument">funerary monument</a> was erected in his memory on the north wall, with a half-effigy of him in the act of writing. Its plaque compares him to <a href="/wiki/Nestor_(mythology)" title="Nestor (mythology)">Nestor</a>, <a href="/wiki/Socrates" title="Socrates">Socrates</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Virgil" title="Virgil">Virgil</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86"><span>[</span>81<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1623, in conjunction with the publication of the <a href="/wiki/First_Folio" title="First Folio">First Folio</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Droeshout_engraving" title="Droeshout engraving" class="mw-redirect">Droeshout engraving</a> was published.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87"><span>[</span>82<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Shakespeare has been commemorated in many <a href="/wiki/Memorials_to_William_Shakespeare" title="Memorials to William Shakespeare">statues and memorials</a> around the world, including funeral monuments in <a href="/wiki/Southwark_Cathedral" title="Southwark Cathedral">Southwark Cathedral</a> and <a href="/wiki/Poets%27_Corner" title="Poets' Corner">Poets' Corner</a> in <a href="/wiki/Westminster_Abbey" title="Westminster Abbey">Westminster Abbey</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Plays">Plays</span></h2>
<div class="center">
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:802px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/800px-Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg" width="800" height="177" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/1200px-Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/1600px-Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 2x" data-file-width="6816" data-file-height="1509" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Procession_of_Characters_from_Shakespeare%27s_Plays_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i>Procession of Characters from Shakespeare's Plays</i> by an unknown artist</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_plays" title="Shakespeare's plays">Shakespeare's plays</a> and <a href="/wiki/William_Shakespeare%27s_collaborations" title="William Shakespeare's collaborations">William Shakespeare's collaborations</a></div>
<p>Most playwrights of the period typically collaborated with others at some point, and critics agree that Shakespeare did the same, mostly early and late in his career.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88"><span>[</span>83<span>]</span></a></sup> Some attributions, such as <i><a href="/wiki/Titus_Andronicus" title="Titus Andronicus">Titus Andronicus</a></i> and the early history plays, remain controversial, while <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Noble_Kinsmen" title="The Two Noble Kinsmen">The Two Noble Kinsmen</a></i> and the lost <i><a href="/wiki/The_History_of_Cardenio" title="The History of Cardenio">Cardenio</a></i> have well-attested contemporary documentation. Textual evidence also supports the view that several of the plays were revised by other writers after their original composition.</p>
<p>The first recorded works of Shakespeare are <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_III_(play)" title="Richard III (play)">Richard III</a></i> and the three parts of <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_VI,_Part_1" title="Henry VI, Part 1">Henry VI</a></i>, written in the early 1590s during a vogue for historical drama. Shakespeare's plays are difficult to date, however,<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89"><span>[</span>84<span>]</span></a></sup> and studies of the texts suggest that <i><a href="/wiki/Titus_Andronicus" title="Titus Andronicus">Titus Andronicus</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Comedy_of_Errors" title="The Comedy of Errors">The Comedy of Errors</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Taming_of_the_Shrew" title="The Taming of the Shrew">The Taming of the Shrew</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Gentlemen_of_Verona" title="The Two Gentlemen of Verona">The Two Gentlemen of Verona</a></i> may also belong to Shakespeare's earliest period.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90"><span>[</span>85<span>]</span></a></sup> His first <a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_history" title="Shakespearean history">histories</a>, which draw heavily on the 1587 edition of <a href="/wiki/Raphael_Holinshed" title="Raphael Holinshed">Raphael Holinshed</a>'s <i>Chronicles of England, Scotland, and Ireland</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91"><span>[</span>86<span>]</span></a></sup> dramatise the destructive results of weak or corrupt rule and have been interpreted as a justification for the origins of the <a href="/wiki/Tudor_dynasty" title="Tudor dynasty">Tudor dynasty</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92"><span>[</span>87<span>]</span></a></sup> The early plays were influenced by the works of other Elizabethan dramatists, especially <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Kyd" title="Thomas Kyd">Thomas Kyd</a> and <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Marlowe" title="Christopher Marlowe">Christopher Marlowe</a>, by the traditions of medieval drama, and by the plays of <a href="/wiki/Seneca_the_Younger" title="Seneca the Younger">Seneca</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93"><span>[</span>88<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>The Comedy of Errors</i> was also based on classical models, but no source for <i>The Taming of the Shrew</i> has been found, though it is related to a separate play of the same name and may have derived from a folk story.<sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94"><span>[</span>89<span>]</span></a></sup> Like <i>The Two Gentlemen of Verona</i>, in which two friends appear to approve of rape,<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95"><span>[</span>90<span>]</span></a></sup> the <i>Shrew's</i> story of the taming of a woman's independent spirit by a man sometimes troubles modern critics and directors.<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96"><span>[</span>91<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Oberon,_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg/220px-Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg" width="220" height="153" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg/330px-Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg/440px-Oberon%2C_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1536" data-file-height="1071" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Oberon,_Titania_and_Puck_with_Fairies_Dancing._William_Blake._c.1786.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i>Oberon, Titania and Puck with Fairies Dancing.</i> By <a href="/wiki/William_Blake" title="William Blake">William Blake</a>, c. 1786. <a href="/wiki/Tate_Britain" title="Tate Britain">Tate Britain</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Shakespeare's early classical and Italianate comedies, containing tight double plots and precise comic sequences, give way in the mid-1590s to the romantic atmosphere of his most acclaimed comedies.<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97"><span>[</span>92<span>]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/A_Midsummer_Night%27s_Dream" title="A Midsummer Night's Dream">A Midsummer Night's Dream</a></i> is a witty mixture of romance, fairy magic, and comic lowlife scenes.<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98"><span>[</span>93<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare's next comedy, the equally romantic <i><a href="/wiki/The_Merchant_of_Venice" title="The Merchant of Venice">Merchant of Venice</a></i>, contains a portrayal of the vengeful Jewish moneylender <a href="/wiki/Shylock" title="Shylock">Shylock</a>, which reflects Elizabethan views but may appear derogatory to modern audiences.<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99"><span>[</span>94<span>]</span></a></sup> The wit and wordplay of <i><a href="/wiki/Much_Ado_About_Nothing" title="Much Ado About Nothing">Much Ado About Nothing</a></i>,<sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100"><span>[</span>95<span>]</span></a></sup> the charming rural setting of <i><a href="/wiki/As_You_Like_It" title="As You Like It">As You Like It</a></i>, and the lively merrymaking of <i><a href="/wiki/Twelfth_Night" title="Twelfth Night">Twelfth Night</a></i> complete Shakespeare's sequence of great comedies.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101"><span>[</span>96<span>]</span></a></sup> After the lyrical <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_II_(play)" title="Richard II (play)">Richard II</a></i>, written almost entirely in verse, Shakespeare introduced prose comedy into the histories of the late 1590s, <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_IV,_Part_1" title="Henry IV, Part 1">Henry IV, parts 1</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_IV,_Part_2" title="Henry IV, Part 2">2</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_V_(play)" title="Henry V (play)">Henry V</a></i>. His characters become more complex and tender as he switches deftly between comic and serious scenes, prose and poetry, and achieves the narrative variety of his mature work.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup> This period begins and ends with two tragedies: <i><a href="/wiki/Romeo_and_Juliet" title="Romeo and Juliet">Romeo and Juliet</a></i>, the famous romantic tragedy of sexually charged adolescence, love, and death;<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103"><span>[</span>98<span>]</span></a></sup> and <i><a href="/wiki/Julius_Caesar_(play)" title="Julius Caesar (play)">Julius Caesar</a></i>—based on Sir <a href="/wiki/Thomas_North" title="Thomas North">Thomas North</a>'s 1579 translation of <a href="/wiki/Plutarch" title="Plutarch">Plutarch</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Parallel_Lives" title="Parallel Lives">Parallel Lives</a></i>—which introduced a new kind of drama.<sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104"><span>[</span>99<span>]</span></a></sup> According to Shakespearean scholar James Shapiro, in <i>Julius Caesar</i> "the various strands of politics, character, inwardness, contemporary events, even Shakespeare's own reflections on the act of writing, began to infuse each other".<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105"><span>[</span>100<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG/220px-Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG" width="220" height="167" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG/330px-Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG/440px-Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2024" data-file-height="1536" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Henry_Fuseli_rendering_of_Hamlet_and_his_father%27s_Ghost.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i>Hamlet, Horatio, Marcellus, and the Ghost of Hamlet's Father.</i> <a href="/wiki/Henry_Fuseli" title="Henry Fuseli">Henry Fuseli</a>, 1780–5. <a href="/wiki/Kunsthaus_Z%C3%BCrich" title="Kunsthaus Zürich">Kunsthaus Zürich</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In the early 17th century, Shakespeare wrote the so-called "<a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_problem_play" title="Shakespearean problem play">problem plays</a>" <i><a href="/wiki/Measure_for_Measure" title="Measure for Measure">Measure for Measure</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Troilus_and_Cressida" title="Troilus and Cressida">Troilus and Cressida</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/All%27s_Well_That_Ends_Well" title="All's Well That Ends Well">All's Well That Ends Well</a></i> and a number of his best known <a href="/wiki/Shakespearean_tragedy" title="Shakespearean tragedy">tragedies</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106"><span>[</span>101<span>]</span></a></sup> Many critics believe that Shakespeare's greatest tragedies represent the peak of his art. The titular hero of one of Shakespeare's most famous tragedies, <i><a href="/wiki/Hamlet" title="Hamlet">Hamlet</a></i>, has probably been discussed more than any other Shakespearean character, especially for his famous <a href="/wiki/Soliloquy" title="Soliloquy">soliloquy</a> which begins "<a href="/wiki/To_be,_or_not_to_be" title="To be, or not to be">To be or not to be; that is the question</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107"><span>[</span>102<span>]</span></a></sup> Unlike the introverted Hamlet, whose fatal flaw is hesitation, the heroes of the tragedies that followed, Othello and King Lear, are undone by hasty errors of judgement.<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108"><span>[</span>103<span>]</span></a></sup> The plots of Shakespeare's tragedies often hinge on such fatal errors or flaws, which overturn order and destroy the hero and those he loves.<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109"><span>[</span>104<span>]</span></a></sup> In <i><a href="/wiki/Othello" title="Othello">Othello</a></i>, the villain <a href="/wiki/Iago" title="Iago">Iago</a> stokes Othello's sexual jealousy to the point where he murders the innocent wife who loves him.<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110"><span>[</span>105<span>]</span></a></sup> In <i><a href="/wiki/King_Lear" title="King Lear">King Lear</a></i>, the old king commits the tragic error of giving up his powers, initiating the events which lead to the torture and blinding of the Earl of Gloucester and the murder of Lear's youngest daughter Cordelia. According to the critic Frank Kermode, "the play-offers neither its good characters nor its audience any relief from its cruelty".<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111"><span>[</span>106<span>]</span></a></sup> In <i><a href="/wiki/Macbeth" title="Macbeth">Macbeth</a></i>, the shortest and most compressed of Shakespeare's tragedies,<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112"><span>[</span>107<span>]</span></a></sup> uncontrollable ambition incites Macbeth and his wife, <a href="/wiki/Lady_Macbeth" title="Lady Macbeth">Lady Macbeth</a>, to murder the rightful king and usurp the throne, until their own guilt destroys them in turn.<sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113"><span>[</span>108<span>]</span></a></sup> In this play, Shakespeare adds a supernatural element to the tragic structure. His last major tragedies, <i><a href="/wiki/Antony_and_Cleopatra" title="Antony and Cleopatra">Antony and Cleopatra</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Coriolanus" title="Coriolanus">Coriolanus</a></i>, contain some of Shakespeare's finest poetry and were considered his most successful tragedies by the poet and critic <a href="/wiki/T._S._Eliot" title="T. S. Eliot">T. S. Eliot</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114"><span>[</span>109<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In his final period, Shakespeare turned to <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_late_romances" title="Shakespeare's late romances">romance</a> or <a href="/wiki/Tragicomedy" title="Tragicomedy">tragicomedy</a> and completed three more major plays: <i><a href="/wiki/Cymbeline" title="Cymbeline">Cymbeline</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Winter%27s_Tale" title="The Winter's Tale">The Winter's Tale</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Tempest" title="The Tempest">The Tempest</a></i>, as well as the collaboration, <i><a href="/wiki/Pericles,_Prince_of_Tyre" title="Pericles, Prince of Tyre">Pericles, Prince of Tyre</a></i>. Less bleak than the tragedies, these four plays are graver in tone than the comedies of the 1590s, but they end with reconciliation and the forgiveness of potentially tragic errors.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115"><span>[</span>110<span>]</span></a></sup> Some commentators have seen this change in mood as evidence of a more serene view of life on Shakespeare's part, but it may merely reflect the theatrical fashion of the day.<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116"><span>[</span>111<span>]</span></a></sup> Shakespeare collaborated on two further surviving plays, <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_VIII_(play)" title="Henry VIII (play)">Henry VIII</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Noble_Kinsmen" title="The Two Noble Kinsmen">The Two Noble Kinsmen</a></i>, probably with <a href="/wiki/John_Fletcher_(playwright)" title="John Fletcher (playwright)">John Fletcher</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117"><span>[</span>112<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Performances">Performances</span></h3>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare_in_performance" title="Shakespeare in performance">Shakespeare in performance</a></div>
<p>It is not clear for which companies Shakespeare wrote his early plays. The title page of the 1594 edition of <i>Titus Andronicus</i> reveals that the play had been acted by three different troupes.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118"><span>[</span>113<span>]</span></a></sup> After the <a href="/wiki/Black_Death" title="Black Death">plagues</a> of 1592–3, Shakespeare's plays were performed by his own company at <a href="/wiki/The_Theatre" title="The Theatre">The Theatre</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Curtain_Theatre" title="Curtain Theatre">Curtain</a> in <a href="/wiki/Shoreditch" title="Shoreditch">Shoreditch</a>, north of the Thames.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119"><span>[</span>114<span>]</span></a></sup> Londoners flocked there to see the first part of <i>Henry IV</i>, <a href="/wiki/Leonard_Digges_(writer)" title="Leonard Digges (writer)">Leonard Digges</a> recording, "Let but Falstaff come, Hal, Poins, the rest...and you scarce shall have a room".<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120"><span>[</span>115<span>]</span></a></sup> When the company found themselves in dispute with their landlord, they pulled The Theatre down and used the timbers to construct the <a href="/wiki/Globe_Theatre" title="Globe Theatre">Globe Theatre</a>, the first playhouse built by actors for actors, on the south bank of the Thames at <a href="/wiki/Southwark" title="Southwark">Southwark</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121"><span>[</span>116<span>]</span></a></sup> The Globe opened in autumn 1599, with <i>Julius Caesar</i> one of the first plays staged. Most of Shakespeare's greatest post-1599 plays were written for the Globe, including <i>Hamlet</i>, <i>Othello</i> and <i>King Lear</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-122" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-122"><span>[</span>117<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Globe_theatre_london.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Globe_theatre_london.jpg/220px-Globe_theatre_london.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Globe_theatre_london.jpg/330px-Globe_theatre_london.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Globe_theatre_london.jpg/440px-Globe_theatre_london.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="450" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Globe_theatre_london.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The reconstructed <a href="/wiki/Globe_Theatre" title="Globe Theatre">Globe Theatre</a>, London.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>After the Lord Chamberlain's Men were renamed the <a href="/wiki/King%27s_Men_(playing_company)" title="King's Men (playing company)">King's Men</a> in 1603, they entered a special relationship with the new <a href="/wiki/James_I_of_England" title="James I of England" class="mw-redirect">King James</a>. Although the performance records are patchy, the King's Men performed seven of Shakespeare's plays at court between 1 November 1604 and 31 October 1605, including two performances of <i>The Merchant of Venice</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-123"><span>[</span>118<span>]</span></a></sup> After 1608, they performed at the indoor <a href="/wiki/Blackfriars_Theatre" title="Blackfriars Theatre">Blackfriars Theatre</a> during the winter and the Globe during the summer.<sup id="cite_ref-124" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124"><span>[</span>119<span>]</span></a></sup> The indoor setting, combined with the <a href="/wiki/Jacobean_era" title="Jacobean era">Jacobean</a> fashion for lavishly staged <a href="/wiki/Masques" title="Masques" class="mw-redirect">masques</a>, allowed Shakespeare to introduce more elaborate stage devices. In <i>Cymbeline</i>, for example, <a href="/wiki/Jupiter_(mythology)" title="Jupiter (mythology)">Jupiter</a> descends "in thunder and lightning, sitting upon an eagle: he throws a thunderbolt. The ghosts fall on their knees."<sup id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125"><span>[</span>120<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The actors in Shakespeare's company included the famous <a href="/wiki/Richard_Burbage" title="Richard Burbage">Richard Burbage</a>, <a href="/wiki/William_Kempe" title="William Kempe">William Kempe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Henry_Condell" title="Henry Condell">Henry Condell</a> and <a href="/wiki/John_Heminges" title="John Heminges">John Heminges</a>. Burbage played the leading role in the first performances of many of Shakespeare's plays, including <i>Richard III</i>, <i>Hamlet</i>, <i>Othello</i>, and <i>King Lear</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-126" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-126"><span>[</span>121<span>]</span></a></sup> The popular comic actor Will Kempe played the servant Peter in <i>Romeo and Juliet</i> and <a href="/wiki/Dogberry" title="Dogberry">Dogberry</a> in <i>Much Ado About Nothing</i>, among other characters.<sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127"><span>[</span>122<span>]</span></a></sup> He was replaced around 1600 by <a href="/wiki/Robert_Armin" title="Robert Armin">Robert Armin</a>, who played roles such as <a href="/wiki/Touchstone_(As_You_Like_It)" title="Touchstone (As You Like It)">Touchstone</a> in <i>As You Like It</i> and the fool in <i>King Lear</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128"><span>[</span>123<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1613, Sir <a href="/wiki/Henry_Wotton" title="Henry Wotton">Henry Wotton</a> recorded that <i>Henry VIII</i> "was set forth with many extraordinary circumstances of pomp and ceremony".<sup id="cite_ref-WellsOxford1247_129-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WellsOxford1247-129"><span>[</span>124<span>]</span></a></sup> On 29 June, however, a cannon set fire to the thatch of the Globe and burned the theatre to the ground, an event which pinpoints the date of a Shakespeare play with rare precision.<sup id="cite_ref-WellsOxford1247_129-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WellsOxford1247-129"><span>[</span>124<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Textual_sources">Textual sources</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg/220px-Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg" width="220" height="350" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg/330px-Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg/440px-Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg 2x" data-file-width="950" data-file-height="1513" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Title_page_William_Shakespeare%27s_First_Folio_1623.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Title page of the <a href="/wiki/First_Folio" title="First Folio">First Folio</a>, 1623. Copper engraving of Shakespeare by <a href="/wiki/Martin_Droeshout" title="Martin Droeshout">Martin Droeshout</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1623, <a href="/wiki/John_Heminges" title="John Heminges">John Heminges</a> and <a href="/wiki/Henry_Condell" title="Henry Condell">Henry Condell</a>, two of Shakespeare's friends from the King's Men, published the <a href="/wiki/First_Folio" title="First Folio">First Folio</a>, a collected edition of Shakespeare's plays. It contained 36 texts, including 18 printed for the first time.<sup id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130"><span>[</span>125<span>]</span></a></sup> Many of the plays had already appeared in <a href="/wiki/Book_size" title="Book size">quarto</a> versions—flimsy books made from sheets of paper folded twice to make four leaves.<sup id="cite_ref-Oxfxxxiv_131-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oxfxxxiv-131"><span>[</span>126<span>]</span></a></sup> No evidence suggests that Shakespeare approved these editions, which the First Folio describes as "stol'n and surreptitious copies".<sup id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132"><span>[</span>127<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Alfred_W._Pollard" title="Alfred W. Pollard">Alfred Pollard</a> termed some of them "<a href="/wiki/Bad_quarto" title="Bad quarto">bad quartos</a>" because of their adapted, paraphrased or garbled texts, which may in places have been reconstructed from memory.<sup id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133"><span>[</span>128<span>]</span></a></sup> Where several versions of a play survive, each <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_plays#Shakespeare_and_the_textual_problem" title="Shakespeare's plays">differs from the other</a>. The differences may stem from copying or <a href="/wiki/Typesetting#Letterpress_era" title="Typesetting">printing</a> errors, from notes by actors or audience members, or from Shakespeare's own <a href="/wiki/Foul_papers" title="Foul papers">papers</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134"><span>[</span>129<span>]</span></a></sup> In some cases, for example <i>Hamlet</i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Troilus_and_Cressida" title="Troilus and Cressida">Troilus and Cressida</a></i> and <i>Othello</i>, Shakespeare could have revised the texts between the quarto and folio editions. In the case of <i><a href="/wiki/King_Lear" title="King Lear">King Lear</a></i>, however, while most modern editions do conflate them, the 1623 folio version is so different from the 1608 quarto, that the <i>Oxford Shakespeare</i> prints them both, arguing that they cannot be conflated without confusion.<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135"><span>[</span>130<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Poems">Poems</span></h2>
<p>In 1593 and 1594, when the theatres were closed because of <a href="/wiki/Bubonic_plague" title="Bubonic plague">plague</a>, Shakespeare published two narrative poems on erotic themes, <i><a href="/wiki/Venus_and_Adonis_(Shakespeare_poem)" title="Venus and Adonis (Shakespeare poem)">Venus and Adonis</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Rape_of_Lucrece" title="The Rape of Lucrece">The Rape of Lucrece</a></i>. He dedicated them to <a href="/wiki/Henry_Wriothesley,_3rd_Earl_of_Southampton" title="Henry Wriothesley, 3rd Earl of Southampton">Henry Wriothesley, Earl of Southampton</a>. In <i>Venus and Adonis</i>, an innocent <a href="/wiki/Adonis" title="Adonis">Adonis</a> rejects the sexual advances of <a href="/wiki/Venus_(mythology)" title="Venus (mythology)">Venus</a>; while in <i>The Rape of Lucrece</i>, the virtuous wife <a href="/wiki/Lucretia" title="Lucretia">Lucrece</a> is raped by the lustful <a href="/wiki/Sextus_Tarquinius" title="Sextus Tarquinius">Tarquin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136"><span>[</span>131<span>]</span></a></sup> Influenced by <a href="/wiki/Ovid" title="Ovid">Ovid</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Metamorphoses" title="Metamorphoses">Metamorphoses</a></i>,<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137"><span>[</span>132<span>]</span></a></sup> the poems show the guilt and moral confusion that result from uncontrolled lust.<sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138"><span>[</span>133<span>]</span></a></sup> Both proved popular and were often reprinted during Shakespeare's lifetime. A third narrative poem, <i><a href="/wiki/A_Lover%27s_Complaint" title="A Lover's Complaint">A Lover's Complaint</a></i>, in which a young woman laments her seduction by a persuasive suitor, was printed in the first edition of the <i>Sonnets</i> in 1609. Most scholars now accept that Shakespeare wrote <i>A Lover's Complaint</i>. Critics consider that its fine qualities are marred by leaden effects.<sup id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-139"><span>[</span>134<span>]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/The_Phoenix_and_the_Turtle" title="The Phoenix and the Turtle">The Phoenix and the Turtle</a></i>, printed in Robert Chester's 1601 <i>Love's Martyr</i>, mourns the deaths of the legendary <a href="/wiki/Phoenix_(mythology)" title="Phoenix (mythology)">phoenix</a> and his lover, the faithful <a href="/wiki/Turtle_dove" title="Turtle dove" class="mw-redirect">turtle dove</a>. In 1599, two early drafts of sonnets 138 and 144 appeared in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Passionate_Pilgrim" title="The Passionate Pilgrim">The Passionate Pilgrim</a></i>, published under Shakespeare's name but without his permission.<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140"><span>[</span>135<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sonnets">Sonnets</span></h3>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_sonnets" title="Shakespeare's sonnets">Shakespeare's sonnets</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg/170px-Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg" width="170" height="245" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg/255px-Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg/340px-Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1065" data-file-height="1536" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Sonnets1609titlepage.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Title page from 1609 edition of <i>Shake-Speares Sonnets</i>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Published in 1609, the <i><a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_sonnets" title="Shakespeare's sonnets">Sonnets</a></i> were the last of Shakespeare's non-dramatic works to be printed. Scholars are not certain when each of the 154 sonnets was composed, but evidence suggests that Shakespeare wrote sonnets throughout his career for a private readership.<sup id="cite_ref-141" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-141"><span>[</span>136<span>]</span></a></sup> Even before the two unauthorised sonnets appeared in <i>The Passionate Pilgrim</i> in 1599, <a href="/wiki/Francis_Meres" title="Francis Meres">Francis Meres</a> had referred in 1598 to Shakespeare's "sugred Sonnets among his private friends".<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142"><span>[</span>137<span>]</span></a></sup> Few analysts believe that the published collection follows Shakespeare's intended sequence.<sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143"><span>[</span>138<span>]</span></a></sup> He seems to have planned two contrasting series: one about uncontrollable lust for a married woman of dark complexion (the "dark lady"), and one about conflicted love for a fair young man (the "fair youth"). It remains unclear if these figures represent real individuals, or if the authorial "I" who addresses them represents Shakespeare himself, though <a href="/wiki/Wordsworth" title="Wordsworth" class="mw-redirect">Wordsworth</a> believed that with the sonnets "Shakespeare unlocked his heart".<sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144"><span>[</span>139<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<div class="quotebox" style="float: right; clear: right; margin: 0.5em 0 0.8em 1.4em; padding: 6px; border: 1px solid #aaa; font-size: 88%; background-color: #F9F9F9;">
<div class="" style="position: relative; text-align: left;">
<div>
<div class="poem">
<p>"Shall I compare thee to a summer's day?<br />
Thou art more lovely and more temperate..."</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div style="text-align: left;">—Lines from Shakespeare's <i><a href="/wiki/Sonnet_18" title="Sonnet 18">Sonnet 18</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145"><span>[</span>140<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
<p>The 1609 edition was dedicated to a "Mr. W.H.", credited as "the only begetter" of the poems. It is not known whether this was written by Shakespeare himself or by the publisher, <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Thorpe" title="Thomas Thorpe">Thomas Thorpe</a>, whose initials appear at the foot of the dedication page; nor is it known who Mr. W.H. was, despite numerous theories, or whether Shakespeare even authorised the publication.<sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146"><span>[</span>141<span>]</span></a></sup> Critics praise the <i>Sonnets</i> as a profound meditation on the nature of love, sexual passion, procreation, death, and time.<sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147"><span>[</span>142<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Style">Style</span></h2>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_style" title="Shakespeare's style">Shakespeare's style</a></div>
<p>Shakespeare's first plays were written in the conventional style of the day. He wrote them in a stylised language that does not always spring naturally from the needs of the characters or the drama.<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148"><span>[</span>143<span>]</span></a></sup> The poetry depends on extended, sometimes elaborate metaphors and conceits, and the language is often rhetorical—written for actors to declaim rather than speak. The grand speeches in <i><a href="/wiki/Titus_Andronicus" title="Titus Andronicus">Titus Andronicus</a></i>, in the view of some critics, often hold up the action, for example; and the verse in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Gentlemen_of_Verona" title="The Two Gentlemen of Verona">The Two Gentlemen of Verona</a></i> has been described as stilted.<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149"><span>[</span>144<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Soon, however, Shakespeare began to adapt the traditional styles to his own purposes. The opening <a href="/wiki/Soliloquy" title="Soliloquy">soliloquy</a> of <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_III_(play)" title="Richard III (play)">Richard III</a></i> has its roots in the self-declaration of <a href="/wiki/The_Vice" title="The Vice" class="mw-redirect">Vice</a> in medieval drama. At the same time, Richard's vivid self-awareness looks forward to the soliloquies of Shakespeare's mature plays.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150"><span>[</span>145<span>]</span></a></sup> No single play marks a change from the traditional to the freer style. Shakespeare combined the two throughout his career, with <i><a href="/wiki/Romeo_and_Juliet" title="Romeo and Juliet">Romeo and Juliet</a></i> perhaps the best example of the mixing of the styles.<sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151"><span>[</span>146<span>]</span></a></sup> By the time of <i>Romeo and Juliet</i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_II_(play)" title="Richard II (play)">Richard II</a></i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/A_Midsummer_Night%27s_Dream" title="A Midsummer Night's Dream">A Midsummer Night's Dream</a></i> in the mid-1590s, Shakespeare had begun to write a more natural poetry. He increasingly tuned his metaphors and images to the needs of the drama itself.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:312px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Pity.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/05/Pity.jpg/310px-Pity.jpg" width="310" height="226" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/05/Pity.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/05/Pity.jpg 2x" data-file-width="411" data-file-height="299" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Pity.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i><a href="/wiki/Pity_(William_Blake)" title="Pity (William Blake)">Pity</a></i> by <a href="/wiki/William_Blake" title="William Blake">William Blake</a>, 1795, <a href="/wiki/Tate_Britain" title="Tate Britain">Tate Britain</a>, is an illustration of two similes in <i>Macbeth</i>:<br />
<i>"And pity, like a naked new-born babe,<br />
Striding the blast, or heaven's cherubim, hors'd<br />
Upon the sightless couriers of the air."</i><sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152"><span>[</span>147<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Shakespeare's standard poetic form was <a href="/wiki/Blank_verse" title="Blank verse">blank verse</a>, composed in <a href="/wiki/Iambic_pentameter" title="Iambic pentameter">iambic pentameter</a>. In practice, this meant that his verse was usually unrhymed and consisted of ten syllables to a line, spoken with a stress on every second syllable. The blank verse of his early plays is quite different from that of his later ones.
